1.
Instead of storing

{
    "customer":"John",
    "interest":"Azure Migration",
    "budget":"30000"
}

We'll store

Customer: John Smith
Company: ABC Ltd
Interest: Azure Migration
Budget: $30000

This is called a Document.

Later, this document gets converted into an embedding.

Why don't we just store JSON?

Because semantic search works on natural language, not JSON objects.

2.
Preparing the documents ✅ (current step)
Generating embeddings and storing them (next step)

If you understand this separation, the rest of the project becomes much easier.

3.
# Think of it as a tiny AI model trained for understanding sentence meaning.
# Example:
# Azure Migration
# ↓
# [0.21, -0.44, 0.17, ...]
embedding_model = SentenceTransformer("all-MiniLM-L6-v2")
# It returns a vector with 384 numbers.
# Those numbers are what ChromaDB searches.

4.
This is probably the single most important concept in RAG, Agentic AI, Semantic Kernel, LangChain, CrewAI—everything.

Let's make it intuitive.

Suppose I write:

Azure Migration

The embedding model sees:

[-0.12,
 0.45,
 0.91,
 ...
 384 numbers]

Now another sentence:

Move my workloads to Azure

becomes

[-0.11,
 0.47,
 0.89,
 ...
 384 numbers]

Notice anything?

The numbers are not identical, but they're very close.

That's because both sentences have the same meaning.

Real-life analogy

Imagine every sentence is a house on a map.

                   AI
                    ▲
                    │
          Azure Migration
                 ●
                / \
               /   \
              /     \
Move workloads ●      ● AWS EC2
Similar meanings are physically close.
Different meanings are far away.
When the user asks:
"Who wants Azure?"
The embedding model converts the question into another point on this map.
Then ChromaDB simply says:
"The closest document is John's."
That's semantic search.


5.
question: why loading all 22 mil parameters of all-MiniLM-L6-v2.
answer: Here is a quick, 5-line summary of how that process works:

The Setup: When you pass a sentence to the model, it first chops it up into numbers (tokens).

The Math: Your computer then mathematically multiplies those tokens against all 22 million of the model's parameters.

The Filter: Those parameters act like a massive filter, sculpting your text into its final numerical vector (embedding).

The Speed: While doing 22 million math problems sounds slow, modern computer chips (GPUs) crunch them all simultaneously in milliseconds.

The Why: This is exactly why the model must be loaded into memory—your computer needs instant access to all 22 million numbers every single time you want to search a sentence!




6.
Cosine similarity measures the direction of the similarities and not the magnitude.
A.B/(||A|| X ||B||) ----> -1 to 1.

Used for doccument similarity and semantic searches.

why only the cosine:
Think of your 384-dimensional space like a giant map where every piece of data is an arrow pointing from the origin (0,0) out to a coordinate.

If you use regular straight-line distance (Euclidean distance), it gets messed up because of document length. A long document might have huge numbers just because it contains more words, pushing its point way out into space, even if it's about the exact same topic as a short document.

Cosine distance fixes this by completely ignoring how long the arrow is. Instead, it only measures the angle between the user's question arrow and the database's document arrow:






6.
What a "Collection" Actually Looks Like

If you could magically open up ChromaDB and look inside your sales-memory collection, it would look almost exactly like a 3-column Excel spreadsheet:

ID (The Name Tag)

Document (The Text)

Embedding (The Math/Encoded Data)

record_001

"Customer: Sahil, Company: MAQ..."

[0.12, -0.55, 0.89, ... 381 more]

record_002

"Customer: John, Company: Apple..."

[-0.41, 0.11, 0.72, ... 381 more]

Do the IDs get encoded later?

No! The IDs are NEVER encoded.
Only the Documents (the text) get encoded into math.

7.
use upsert instead of add to avoid duplicates
DOCUEMNT.upsert()

8.
The UUID folder stores the actual vector index and associated files used for efficient similarity search.

9.
You'll see this parameter:

n_results=2

This means

Return the Top 2 most similar documents.

This is called Top-K Retrieval.

10.
Now let's understand how Semantic Kernel fits into RAG

This is the architecture we're building.

                ┌────────────────────────┐
                │   User Question        │
                └────────────┬───────────┘
                             │
                             ▼
                   Embedding Model
                             │
                             ▼
                      ChromaDB Search
                             │
                             ▼
                  Retrieved CRM Documents
                             │
                             ▼
               Build Augmented Prompt
                             │
                             ▼
                  Semantic Kernel
                             │
                             ▼
                      Grok / Groq
                             │
                             ▼
                     Final Response

Notice something...

Semantic Kernel doesn't replace ChromaDB.

Semantic Kernel is responsible for:

managing prompts
calling the LLM
orchestrating plugins/functions (later)

ChromaDB is still responsible for retrieval.

11.
New Concept: Context

Suppose ChromaDB returned

Customer: John Smith
Interest: Azure Migration

Customer: Alice Johnson
Interest: Microsoft Fabric

We'll combine them into one string.

context = """

Customer: John Smith
Interest: Azure Migration

Customer: Alice Johnson
Interest: Microsoft Fabric

"""

This string is called the Context.

12.
| Component           | Job                                                                 |
| ------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| SentenceTransformer | Understands semantic meaning and converts text → vectors            |
| ChromaDB            | Retrieves the most relevant information                             |
| Groq (LLM)          | Reads retrieved information and generates a natural-language answer |

